revision.text:
{{Infobox holiday |holiday_name = Ask a Stupid Question Day |type = |image = |imagesize = |caption = |official_name = |nickname = |observedby =some schools in the United States |litcolor = |longtype = |significance = |begins = |ends = |date = September 28 or last school day of September |celebrations = |observances = |frequency = annual |relatedto = }} '''Ask a Stupid Question Day''' is a [[holiday]] that is sometimes celebrated in the [[United States]], usually by school [[student]]s and [[teacher]]s.<ref>[http://www.goofball.com/news/20010906_bizarre Bizarre National Holidays - Goofball.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928080823/http://www.goofball.com/news/20010906_bizarre |date=September 28, 2007 }}</ref> Although Ask a Stupid Question Day's default date is September 28, in practice it is usually observed on the last school day of September.<ref>[http://www.boston.com/yourlife/gallery/stupid_question/ Suggestions for 'Ask a stupid question day' - Boston.com]</ref>
==Origin== This holiday was created by teachers in the 1980s to encourage students to ask more questions in the classroom.<ref>[http://dir.yahoo.com/thespark/8541/ask-a-stupid-question-day/ Ask a Stupid Question Day - The Spark of Yahoo!] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111121022824/http://dir.yahoo.com/thespark/8541/ask-a-stupid-question-day/ |date=November 21, 2011 }}</ref> According to HolidayInsights.com, "at the time, there was a movement by teachers to try to get kids to ask more questions in the classroom. Kids sometimes hold back, fearing their question is stupid, and asking it will result in ridicule."<ref>[http://www.holidayinsights.com/moreholidays/September/stupidquestionday.htm Holiday Insights : May 4 Holiday - Ask a Stupid Question Day<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
==International== In 2009 ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that the day was being celebrated in Britain.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chivers|first=Tom|title=Ask A Stupid Question Day comes to British schools|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/6238694/Ask-A-Stupid-Question-Day-comes-to-British-schools.html|accessdate=15 January 2014|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=28 Sep 2009}}</ref> It has been reported as far afield as India, in ''[[The Hindu]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gayathri|first=Krishnan|title=What’s the question?|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/kids/whats-the-question/article5185324.ece|accessdate=15 January 2014|newspaper=The Hindu|date=September 30, 2013}}</ref>
